'''Dobravac''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|Добравац}}; {{floruit}} 1280) or '''Dobravec''' (Добравец) was a Serbian nobleman serving in the crown land of [[Zahumlje|Hum]], with the title of ''[[tepčija]]''. He is mentioned in a document dated 1280 as serving the countess of Hum ({{small|Moysa serviens Dobraveçi tepçi domine comitisse de Chelmo}}).{{sfn|Blagojević|2001|p=28}} He had a clerk or assistant, Mojše, who sold two of his bondmaids in [[Dubrovnik|Ragusa (Dubrovnik)]] that year.{{sfn|Blagojević|2001|p=28}} Although Dobravac's jurisdiction is unknown from the quotation, he was not a ''[[veliki tepčija]]'' (serving the king directly); his office was limited to the Hum land, but his type of work was the same as that of the ''veliki tepčija''.{{sfn|Blagojević|2001|p=28}} The ''tepčija'' had executive authorities; his ''[[sebri|otroci]]'' ({{singular abbr}} ''otrok''), were servants, lesser in rank but not slaves.<ref>{{cite book|title=Историски гласник: орган Историского друштва НР Србије|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Mo5pAAAAMAAJ|year=1975|publisher=Научна књига|page=25|quote=<!--Добравца-->}}</ref>

==Annotations==
The name is an old Serbian name,<ref>{{cite book|author=Velibor Lazarević|title=Srpski imenoslov: odabrane rukoveti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8GEcAQAAIAAJ|year=2001|publisher=Book|page=65}}</ref> found in medieval [[epigraphy]].

