'''''Hidden Worlds: Fresh Clues to the Past''''' is a 1974 book, by M. Van Der Veer and P. Moerman, that describes the existence of a previously unidentified [[Civilization|ancient civilization]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Hidden Worlds: Fresh Clues to the Past by M.H.J. Th. van der Veer and P. Moerman |url=http://retrobookshop.com/hiddenworldsfreshcluestothepastbymhjthvanderveerandpmoerman.aspx |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120720024303/http://retrobookshop.com/hiddenworldsfreshcluestothepastbymhjthvanderveerandpmoerman.aspx |dead-url=yes |archive-date=20 July 2012 |work=RETROBOOKSHOP.com |publisher=RETROBOOKSHOP.com |accessdate=17 May 2012 }}</ref>  that was subsequently [[wikt:destroy|destroyed]] by a [[natural disaster]].<ref>M.J.H.T.Van Der Veer, P. Moerman, Hidden Worlds: Fresh Clues to the Past, 1975 edition {{ISBN|0-552-10041-2}}</ref>

''Hidden Worlds: Fresh Clues to the Past'' is a [[wikt:reject|rejection]] of [[Von Daniken|Von Daniken's]] theories;<ref>{{cite web|title=Switzerland: Journey into the unknown|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/europe/switzerland/729363/Switzerland-Journey-into-the-unknown.html|work=Telegraph Travel|publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited|accessdate=17 May 2012|author=Sue Atwood|date=29 December 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The A.A.S. R.A. - Archaeology, Astronautics and SETI Research Association|url=http://www.legendarytimes.com/index.php?op=page&pid=1&PHPSESSID=403a2de5ea7b178df2040f5904ecb1b8|work=Legendary Times|publisher=A.A.S. R.A. (Archaeology, Astronautics & SETI Research Association)|accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Ancient astronauts|url=http://www.skepdic.com/vondanik.html|work=The Skeptics Dictionary|publisher=Robert T. Carroll|accessdate=17 May 2012}}</ref>    however, Der Veer and P.Moerman [[wikt:concede|concede]] the existence of [[Atlantis]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Legend of Atlantis |url=http://www.uri.edu/endeavor/thera/atlantis.html |work=Thera Expedition |publisher=http://www.uri.edu |accessdate=18 May 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206115642/http://www.uri.edu/endeavor/thera/atlantis.html |archivedate=6 February 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The wave that destroyed Atlantis|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/6568053.stm|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=18 May 2012|author=Harvey Lilley|format=News article|date=20 April 2007}}</ref>   The book contests [[Orthodoxy|orthodox]] [[history]], claiming international [[Human settlement|settlement]]  in the [[Americas]] prior to [[European colonization of the Americas|European colonization of the region]] by [[Christopher Columbus]] in 1492.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who Discovered America? Not Christopher Columbus, That's for Certain |url=http://voices.yahoo.com/who-discovered-america-not-christopher-columbus-thats-4638011.html?cat=37 |work=Yahoo! Voices |publisher=Yahoo! News Network |accessdate=18 May 2012 |author=Saul Relative |date=12 October 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120609045208/http://voices.yahoo.com/who-discovered-america-not-christopher-columbus-thats-4638011.html?cat=37 |archivedate=9 June 2012 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Africa's 'greatest explorer'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/1068950.stm|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|accessdate=18 May 2012|author=Joan Baxter|format=News article|date=13 December 2000}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Columbus might have been a Viking disciple |url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/doubleissue/mysteries/columbus.htm |work=U.S News Online |publisher=U.S.News & World Report Inc. |accessdate=18 May 2012 |author=BRUCE B. AUSTER |format=Article |date=24 July 2000 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428010245/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/doubleissue/mysteries/columbus.htm |archivedate=28 April 2012 |df= }}</ref>

Until 1974, M. Van Der Veer and P. Moerman were both [[Painting|painters]], neither holding [[Academia|academic]]-level scientific [[wikt:qualification|qualifications]] or [[credential]]s; subsequently, [[review]]ers criticized their work as [[pseudoarchaeology]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=HoZdcomupUQC&pg=PA45&dq=hidden+worlds+veer+moerman&hl=en&ei=znbiTe_jFYqo8QOZ__WkBw&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=book-preview-link&resnum=3&ved=0CDUQuwUwAg#v=onepage&q=hidden%20worlds%20veer%20moerman&f=false Review in the New Scientist Jul 4, 1974]</ref>

