{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}} {{Use British English|date=December 2016}} The '''Leawood Pump House''' (also known as High Peak Pump House) was built near [[Cromford]], [[Derbyshire]], England in 1849 to supply water to the [[Cromford Canal]], built some 50 years previously.<ref>''Civil Engineering Heritage, eastern and central England'', E. A. Labrum</ref> It is a [[Grade II*]] listed building.<ref name="Listing">{{NHLE |num=1247889 |desc=High Peak Pump House |access-date=5 March 2017 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref> [[File:Leawood.jpg|thumb|right|Leawood pump house]]
Located a little along the canal towpath from [[High Peak Junction]], it stands to a height of {{convert|45|ft}} on the right bank of the [[River Derwent, Derbyshire|River Derwent]], at the end of the Derwent Aqueduct, and has a {{convert|95|ft|adj=on}} chimney stack with a cast-iron cap.
The [[Watt steam engine|Watt-type beam engine]] was designed and erected by Graham and Company of Milton Works, [[Elsecar]], Sheffield. The beam length is {{convert|33|ft}}, the piston diameter {{convert|50|in|m}}, stroke of {{convert|10|ft}} and the engine works at 7 strokes per minute. The boilers, replaced in 1900, have a pressure of 40 p.s.i.
Water is drawn from the River Derwent through a {{convert|150|yd|adj=on}} tunnel to a reservoir in the basement. It is then lifted {{convert|30|ft}} and discharged into the canal.
The immense size of the pump (which can transfer almost four tons of water per stroke and seven strokes a minute, a total of over 39,000 tons of water per 24 hours) is explained by the fact that there were restrictions on removing water from the Derwent river, this being allowed only between 8 p.m. on Saturdays and 8 p.m. on Sundays.
The pumphouse worked continuously from 1849 until 1944 when the canal closed. It was restored in 1979 by the Cromford Canal Society and is run periodically.
